UML:TaggedValue.value: This package contains components associated with the Open Geospatial Consortium Sensor Web Enablement initiative

Package of concrete feature types used in the context of observations. General observations may be made on _any_ feature type (?) but some features-of-interest would not be instantiated if the observation activity was not taking place. Thus these feature types that are only used for observations are intrinsically part of the observations package ...

This request is intended to obtain a complete description of the observation procedure/sensor *including* event-specific parameters. The standard DescribeSensor operation is intended to obtain the "generic" description, i.e. not including any event-specific parameters. So in SOS this information is probably only available in the context of an actual observation event. A (link to the) description of the procedure should be provided on the Observation response to the GetObservation request, so to get more information, it is probably necessary for the client to traverse this link - i.e. _not_ a standard SOS operation. This may be to a Sensor Register or to another service altogether (which may be colocated with the SOS of course).
- Authur, Mark and Walli to confirm

The standard DescribeSensor operation is intended to obtain the "generic" description, i.e. not including any event-specific parameters. So in SOS this information is probably only available in the context of an actual observation event. The eventTime is modelled as a generalized TimeObject. It will often be a geometric primitive, such as an instant or period, but (e.g.) recurrent events may be associated with a temporal geometric complex.
"source" describes the pre-conditions or input-state; "product" the post-conditions or result-state.

EA-notes: Classes derived from Observation may override the type of the "result" property with an appropriate type.
The Observation feature supports an event-centric or user-centric view. The "observation" description is a map of all of the properties associated with a particular information capture event, including its result.
This contrasts with the Sensor feature, which provides a process-centric viewpoint. The "sensor system" description is effectively a map of of the properties of all potential information capture events _except_ the results.

procedure must be suitable for observedProperty
result type must be suitable for observedProperty

UML:TaggedValue.value: Pointer to an observation that provides an estimate of a property value
Pointer to the feature for which the observation provides a estimate of a property-value

The procedure that is the target of this association will often not be observation-instance specific, but rather a description of a generic procedure, instrument, etc. However, if it is necessary to record instance-specific details, parameters, inputs, etc, then a specific procedure-instance or procedure-event may be used. Alternatively, event-specific parameters (e.g. calibrations) may be recorded in the eventParameter property on the Observation instance.

The procedure that is the target of this association will usually be a description of a generic procedure, activity, instrument, etc. However, if it is necessary to record event-specific details, parameters, inputs, calibrations, etc, then either (i) eventParameter(s) may be used, or (ii) a specific procedure-instance may be used. For example, a CategoryObservation event will use a classification-procedure that may depend on more primitive observations - e.g. a set of prior measurements. As part of the description of the procedure it may be useful to be able to record these sources or inputs. It is preferable to partition these considerations with the "Procedure" rather than promoting special properties ("inputs", "source") up to the Observation class. This is consistent with some mission-specific parameters being associated with the sensor, as is done in SensorML. However, the most appropriate partioning of the generic (static) and instance specific (dynamic) information between the Observation feature and the Procedure/Sensor is to some extent arbitrary.
The Procedure must be commensurate with the Phenomenon being observed. The phenomenon-definition is treated as a first-class property of observation in order to support discovery and data fusion.

Convenience observation type where the result is a text value from some controlled vocabulary or authority or follows some lexical pattern. The source of the vocabulary, authority, or pattern for the result (its "codeSpace") is defined separately, and indicated via a URI link from the result to the codeSpace definition.
Add sequence# XML attribute to explicitly capture step sequence
Generic class for description of procedures. In the context of observations these may be specialized as Sensors and Instruments, Calculations and Simulators.
If present, this indicates that the object represents an instance. If not, the object represents a type.
"source" describes the pre-conditions or input-state; "product" the post-conditions or result-state.

Thus these feature types that are only used for observations are intrinsically part of the observations package ...

Provisional
Specialised coverage used to record the set of offset,direction values conventionally used when surveying a traverse, borehole, etc
Required if position CRS is 2D; DirectPosition in this case will be a 1D coordinate in a 1D CRS (i.e. a datum and scale)

Site is the top of a hierarchy of classes describing features whose primary role is to provide locations for sampling and in-situ observations, such as Station, Traverse, Section, Borehole, Flightline. Instances of these feature-types are not defined by the variation of any intrinsic property, such as a geological concept, but are artefacts of the observation process, either conceptual or constructed.
Generic property; its value is provided by a relatedObservation
Optional pointer to the domain feature that the specimen samples
Maybe need a more specialized SamplingProcedure hierarchy (derived from ProcedureType)

A Specimen is some physical material sampled from a specified location, typically associated with a Site, such as a Station, a location or interval within a Section, or a location or extent from a DescriptionExtent
Current location of specimen, e.g. storage location
Basic material classification, e.g. soil, water, rock, tissue
For more detailed constraints, must use sensor response model
